where I've been the last ten years.

267
00:27:20,642 --> 00:27:22,144
Well...

268
00:27:22,227 --> 00:27:23,938
Tell 'em you went crazy.

269
00:27:24,856 --> 00:27:27,358
Tell 'em you've been locked up.

270
00:27:29,068 --> 00:27:31,237
That's what I've been telling 'em.

271
00:27:31,320 --> 00:27:33,322
Looks like we did real good today.

272
00:27:33,405 --> 00:27:35,867
Guess I got you to thank for that.

273
00:27:35,950 --> 00:27:39,119
Maybe I'll have some music
on Saturday night.

274
00:27:39,202 --> 00:27:44,333
Of course, then again,
you'd have to dance with Billy and Wayne.

275
00:27:44,959 --> 00:27:47,128
Oh, that'd be a sight.

276
00:28:01,934 --> 00:28:03,853
Can I help you?

277
00:28:06,271 --> 00:28:08,440
I'm Einar Gilkyson's daughter-in-law.

278
00:28:08,482 --> 00:28:11,610
Yes, I know.
Did you want to come in?

279
00:28:14,530 --> 00:28:16,615
Thank you.

280
00:28:16,699 --> 00:28:18,617
- Any calls?
- Nothing.

281
00:28:23,246 --> 00:28:25,499
Homemade lunch, you know.

282
00:28:31,965 --> 00:28:35,343
You got something there
you want me to see?

283
00:28:41,516 --> 00:28:45,228
It's a police report.
But I didn't press charges.

284
00:28:45,269 --> 00:28:51,318
A shelter worker in Iowa thought I ought to
check in with authorities when I got settled.

285
00:28:52,443 --> 00:28:55,155
He was my boyfriend.

286
00:28:55,197 --> 00:28:57,282
But, um...

287
00:28:57,365 --> 00:28:59,867
The report's not for this time.

288
00:29:00,660 --> 00:29:02,746
It was for another time.

289
00:29:05,916 --> 00:29:08,001
I'll make a copy.

290
00:29:20,013 --> 00:29:21,181
That's it.

291
00:29:26,228 --> 00:29:28,271
What are their names?

292
00:29:29,188 --> 00:29:31,691
- Who?
- Your cats.

293
00:29:32,734 --> 00:29:35,445
They don't have any names.

294
00:29:37,280 --> 00:29:39,117
How do you tell 'em apart?

295
00:29:39,992 --> 00:29:41,952
I don't tell 'em apart.

296
00:29:47,958 --> 00:29:51,796
Goddamn cheap-ass, Mickey Mouse,
foreign goddamn part...

297
00:29:51,879 --> 00:29:54,090
Oscar and Charlie.

298
00:29:54,173 --> 00:29:56,175
Hi, Charlie.

299
00:29:56,258 --> 00:29:58,802
Is that there a water-pump belt?

300
00:29:59,762 --> 00:30:02,139
Why don't you use the one
out on the tractor?

301
00:30:02,222 --> 00:30:04,183
Why don't I use the one
out on the tractor?

302
00:30:04,266 --> 00:30:07,353
Hey, are you mumbling
over there or something?

303
00:30:07,436 --> 00:30:09,646
The tractor belt's twice this size.

304
00:30:09,730 --> 00:30:11,482
- Really?
- Yeah.

305
00:30:11,523 --> 00:30:13,400
Oh.

306
00:30:14,110 --> 00:30:16,612
Don't we have some
spare belts in the barn?

307
00:30:16,695 --> 00:30:20,532
I got a great idea.
Why don't you go back in the house?

308
00:30:20,616 --> 00:30:25,329
Well, uh, damn. I was...
just trying to be helpful.

309
00:30:25,413 --> 00:30:29,250
If you don't want my help,
I'll just sit over here and shut up.

310
00:30:29,333 --> 00:30:32,336
Pulling that out, it don't look like
you know what you're doing.

311
00:30:32,420 --> 00:30:35,630
Just shut up! OK?
Shut up. You don't know what I'm doing.

312
00:30:35,714 --> 00:30:38,175
- You don't know about the truck.
- Who you talking to?

313
00:30:38,259 --> 00:30:42,554
- Stop being a philosopher...
- Doggone second-generation immigrant,

314
00:30:42,638 --> 00:30:45,808
I bet I come over there
and hang my bad foot in your ass.

315
00:30:56,945 --> 00:30:58,905
- Thanks.
- Anytime.

316
00:30:58,988 --> 00:31:01,532
- See you tomorrow?
- Yep. See ya.

317
00:31:02,659 --> 00:31:04,202
- Hey, kiddo.
- Hey.

318
00:31:04,285 --> 00:31:06,246
- How was it?
- All right.

319
00:31:07,247 --> 00:31:10,625
- See ya, Einar.
- Got some groceries for dinner.

320
00:31:13,420 --> 00:31:15,088
OK.

321
00:31:17,924 --> 00:31:20,702
- Do you wanna take these inside, sweetie?
- Sure.

322
00:31:20,802 --> 00:31:22,179
- Got it?
- Yep.

323
00:31:23,471 --> 00:31:26,016
- Hey, Mitch.
- Hey, there.

324
00:31:29,936 --> 00:31:34,023
What happened here?
Why did you stop running cows?

325
00:31:35,358 --> 00:31:37,610
When Griffin died, I ran out of help.

326
00:31:40,197 --> 00:31:43,449
Then I got older, Mitch got mauled,

327
00:31:44,326 --> 00:31:47,496
and I sold the stock to stay on the place.

328
00:31:50,873 --> 00:31:53,376
Dinner will be ready in an hour.

329
00:31:55,712 --> 00:31:57,630
Come here, Sarah.

330
00:31:58,507 --> 00:32:00,801
Nope, stay here.

331
00:32:00,843 --> 00:32:03,095
- You finished?
- Yeah.

332
00:32:03,845 --> 00:32:07,224
Tell your kid to come down
out of that tree.

333
00:32:09,476 --> 00:32:12,104
Come on, Charlie.

334
00:32:12,188 --> 00:32:14,648
Come on.
Don't be a fraidy-cat.

335
00:32:23,199 --> 00:32:24,992
Oh, Jesus.

336
00:32:26,827 --> 00:32:28,704
I'm sorry.

337
00:32:28,787 --> 00:32:32,458
You're sorry, huh?
Well, that's just fine, then.

338
00:32:33,250 --> 00:32:37,213
- I'll buy you a new one.
- Oh. Just that easy?

339
00:32:38,797 --> 00:32:43,469
Maybe I liked that plate. In fact, maybe
that was my favorite goddamn plate!

340
00:32:43,552 --> 00:32:45,554
- It's just a plate.
- That's it, huh?

341
00:32:45,596 --> 00:32:49,058
Did it ever occur to you
that not everything can be replaced?

342
00:32:56,190 --> 00:32:58,567
Come down out of that tree!

343
00:33:05,449 --> 00:33:09,829
- You want this on the table?
- No, over here. Thank you.

344
00:33:12,791 --> 00:33:15,126
I'm so glad you're back, Jean.

345
00:33:23,802 --> 00:33:26,012
What happened to Nellie?

346
00:33:28,222 --> 00:33:30,308
Nellie left.

347
00:33:30,391 --> 00:33:33,353
About a year after we buried Griffin.

348
00:33:34,563 --> 00:33:37,440
Einar just never got a handle on it.

349
00:33:37,523 --> 00:33:41,194
And then, when he hardly
even noticed Nellie anymore, why...

350
00:33:41,277 --> 00:33:44,239
She found another man.
Who wouldn't?

351
00:33:45,407 --> 00:33:47,742
Think they live in Colorado.

352
00:33:49,161 --> 00:33:53,164
Do you think he blames me
for losing his wife too?

353
00:33:53,248 --> 00:33:55,125
I imagine he does.

354
00:34:05,092 --> 00:34:07,596
I don't want to stay here.

355
00:34:09,889 --> 00:34:11,808
